{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 10:52:20.534457", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos (EBGP) topology\\n\\nScope and method\\n- I examined data-plane reachability between hosts and the control-plane (FRR BGP and routing tables) on all routers. Tools used: reachability (host pings), frr_get_bgp_conf on all FRR routers, and frr_show_ip_route on all FRR routers.\\n- Focus: detect anomalies, localize faulty devices (if any), identify root causes. No remediation proposed.\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Overall state: healthy. End-to-end connectivity between hosts (pc_0_0 ↔ pc_0_1) is working and BGP control-plane has converged across leaves, spines and super-spine.\\n- No device shows BGP session down or missing prefixes. All expected prefixes (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) are present in BGP on all routers and installed in the routing table where appropriate.\\n- No routing leaks, route blackholes, or obvious configuration errors were observed from the collected outputs.\\n\\nData-plane (host reachability)\\n- pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) → pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2): 0% loss, avg RTT ≈ 3.19 ms (2 pings).\\n- pc_0_1 → pc_0_0: 0% loss, avg RTT ≈ 2.85 ms (2 pings).\\n- Interpretation: traffic forwarding between pods/leaves is functional.\\n\\nControl-plane (BGP) — key observations per router\\n- leaf_router_0_0 (local AS 65200, router-id 172.16.0.5)\\n  - Locally connected: 10.0.0.0/24 (C).\\n  - Learned 10.0.1.0/24 via two EBGP paths (next-hops shown: 172.16.0.8 and 172.16.0.4). BGP has multiple paths available; route to remote 10.0.1.0/24 is in RIB and FIB via 172.16.0.4.\\n  - Routing table: 10.0.0.0/24 directly connected eth2; 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4 (eth0).\\n\\n- leaf_router_0_1 (local AS 65201, router-id 172.16.0.7)\\n  - Locally connected: 10.0.1.0/24.\\n  - Learned 10.0.0.0/24 via two EBGP paths (next-hops 172.16.0.10 and 172.16.0.6). The RIB/FIB uses next-hop 172.16.0.6.\\n  - Routing table consistent: direct 10.0.1.0/24 on eth2; 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.6 (eth0).\\n\\n- spine_router_0_0 (local AS 65100, router-id 172.16.0.1)\\n  - Sees 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.5 and 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7 (both EBGP). Both prefixes are present in BGP table.\\n  - Routing table shows next-hops consistent with BGP.\\n\\n- spine_router_0_1 (local AS 65101, router-id 172.16.0.3)\\n  - Sees multiple paths for each prefix, including paths traversing the super-spine (AS 65000) and direct spine→leaf paths. Best-path selection picks a direct spine path per prefix (e.g., 10.0.0.0 via 172.16.0.9, 10.0.1.0 via 172.16.0.11).\\n  - Multiple available paths are expected in a Clos/fat-tree and provide redundancy.\\n\\n- super_spine_router_0 (local AS 65000, router-id 172.16.0.0)\\n  - Receives both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 from both spine routers. Best-path selection shows 172.16.0.1 (spine_router_0_0) is chosen for both prefixes in the outputs observed.\\n  - Routing table shows the two spine links (/31s) connected and the BGP-learned prefixes via the spines.\\n\\nControl-plane consistency checks and notable details\\n- Prefix visibility: Both leaf-originated /24s (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) are advertised and visible in the BGP tables of all upstream routers (spines and super-spine).\\n- Path multiplicity: Several routers show multiple AS‑path alternatives for each prefix (direct spine→leaf paths and paths via super-spine). This is expected in this architecture and provides redundancy. Best-path selection appears consistent (no conflicting selection policies observed).\\n- Local origination: Each leaf shows its connected /24 as locally originated (weight 32768 on local origin entries), and that entry is distributed.\\n- Routing entries in the kernel (C and B entries) align with the BGP table selection — learned prefixes are in the routing table with appropriate next-hops.\\n- No BGP session flaps or withdrawn prefixes were seen in the snapshots collected.\\n\\nAnomalies / potential concerns\\n- None identified from available data. Specifically:\\n  - No missing routes for the hosts’ /24s on any router.\\n  - No BGP sessions in Idle/Active/Connect state reported in the sampled BGP outputs; sessions appear established (routes learned).\\n  - Data-plane tests (pings) succeeded with low latency and no loss.\\n\\nAdditional notes (informational)\\n- Asymmetric best-paths / multiple AS‑path alternatives exist (e.g., spine_router_0_1 showing paths that traverse AS 65000). This is normal in a Clos fabric where multiple equal/alternative interconnects exist; it can cause asymmetry in forwarding but is not an error per se.\\n- If deeper temporal analysis is required (BGP neighbor state history, counters, log messages, or to detect intermittent flaps), gather show ip bgp summary, neighbor counters, and router logs over time. (No remediation recommended here; just note for possible future troubleshooting.)\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network is converged and functioning: BGP control-plane is established across leaves, spines, and super-spine; routing tables are populated and consistent with BGP; data-plane connectivity between hosts is verified.\\n- No faulty devices or immediate control-/data-plane anomalies were detected from the provided snapshots.\\n\\nIf you want, I can:\\n- Dump BGP neighbor summaries and BGP neighbor counters (show ip bgp summary / show bgp neighbors) for more detail.\\n- Pull FRR logs or stream BGP events over a short interval to detect intermittent flaps., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='38574e05-9f2c-4c08-8a91-6f97f4407e72'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
